  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "lesson-14",
      "name": "Introduction to Music Lab",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Question of the Day:** How can we choose a song design based on the needs of a user?\n\nTo kick off a unit focused on creative coding and designing interactive music experiences, students will take on the role of music experience designers. Their challenge: help clients bring their ideas for unique songs to life using Music Lab.\n\nStudents begin by reviewing a variety of early song prototypes in Code Studio, each showcasing different interactive features. Then, they read through short client stories—each with a specific goal or mood in mind—and match each client with the prototype that best fits their vision.\n\nTo wrap up, students reflect on how understanding a user’s goals can shape creative decisions and consider how they might adapt or remix prototypes in Music Lab to better serve different needs.",
        "preparation": "* Print a copy of the activity guide for each student\n- Preview the prototype examples in Code Studio to get familiar with the student experience\n- Check the [\"Teacher's Lounge\"](https://forum.code.org/t/resource-hub-web-development-chapter-1/36190) forum for verified teachers to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "Today, you’ll be a music experience designer! Your job is to help different “clients” bring their song ideas to life. First, you’ll check out some song prototypes in Music Lab. Then, you’ll read each client’s story and decide which prototype fits their idea best.\n\nYou’ll explain your choice and think about how to make the music even better for them."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-14",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "musiclab-6-12-playground"
      }
    },
